The linearity property of conditional expectation states that for any two integrable random variables X and Y on a probability space (Ω, 𝓕, P), any sub-σ-algebra 𝒢 ⊆ 𝓕, and any constants a, b ∈ ℝ, we have E[aX + bY | 𝒢] = a·E[X | 𝒢] + b·E[Y | 𝒢], almost surely. This equality holds P-almost surely rather than pointwise, since conditional expectations are only defined up to sets of measure zero. The property extends by induction to any finite linear combination: E[∑ᵢ aᵢXᵢ | 𝒢] = ∑ᵢ aᵢ·E[Xᵢ | 𝒢] a.s., provided each Xᵢ is integrable. It follows directly from the defining properties of conditional expectation — namely 𝒢-measurability and the partial averaging identity ∫_A E[X | 𝒢] dP = ∫_A X dP for all A ∈ 𝒢 — combined with the linearity of the Lebesgue integral. Linearity is one of the fundamental properties of E[· | 𝒢], alongside the tower property, taking out what is known, positivity, and Jensen's inequality.
